04716nam a22005655i 9780823285242DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232852427 a10.1515/97808232852422doi  a(DE-B1597)555415  a(OCoLC)1175633368  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB945.P44bR4 2019 7aPHI0200002bisacsh04a001.42012231 aReilly, Francis E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCharles Peirce's Theory of Scientific Method /cFrancis E. Reilly. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tI CHARLES SANDERS PEIRCE: PHILOSOPHER, SCIENTIST, WRITER -- tII THE SCIENTIST'S CONCERN: KNOWLEDGE FOR ITS OWN SAKE -- tIII THE STAGES OF THE METHOD (i): EXPERIENCE AND HYPOTHESIS -- tIV THE STAGES OF THE METHOD (ii): DEDUCTION AND INDUCTION -- tV THE MODERATE FALLIBILISM OF SCIENCE -- tVI SOME EVALUATIONS -- tAPPENDIX -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis book is an attempt to understand a significant part of the complex thought of Charles Sanders Peirce, especially in those areas which interested him most: scientific method and related philosophical questions. It is organized primarily from Peirce's own writings, taking chronological settings into account where appropriate, and pointing out the close connections of several major themes in Peirce's work which show the rich diversity of his thought and its systematic unity. Following an introductory sketch of Peirce the thinking and writer is a study of the spirit and phases of scientific inquiry, and a consideration of its relevance to certain outstanding philosophical views which Peirce held. This double approach is necessary because his views on scientific method are interlaces with a profound and elaborate philosophy of the cosmos. Peirce's thought is unusually close-knit, and his difficulty as a writer lies in his inability to achieve a partial focus without bringing into view numerous connections and relations with the whole picture of reality. Peirce received some of the esteem he deserves when the publication of his Collected Papers began more than thirty-five years ago. Some reviewers and critics, however, have attempted to fit Peirce into their own molds in justification of a particular position; others have disinterestedly sought to present him in completely detached fashion. Here, the author has attempted to understand Peirce as Peirce intended himself to be understood, and has presented what he believes Perice's philosophy of scientific method to be. He singles out for praise Peirce's Greek insistence on the primacy of theoretical knowledge and his almost Teilhardian synthesis of evolutionary themes. Primarily philosophical, this volume analyzes Peirce's thought using a theory of knowledge and metaphysics rather than formal logic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSciencexMethodologyxPhilosophy. 0aSciencexMethodology. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Pragmatism.2bisacsh1 aReily, Francis E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311072273440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823285242?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823285242zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruy